A correct way to declare a dynamically allocated 2D integer array with r rows and c columns in C is by using the function malloc(). By doing so, memory is allocated for the array elements in the heap, and a pointer to the beginning of the array is returned. To declare a 2D integer array using malloc(), the syntax is: 

int *arr = malloc(r * c * sizeof(int));

This line allocates memory for r * c integer elements using the malloc() function and assigns the pointer to arr.
